    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-12-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-06-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="702" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d702">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>The delegates returned to Panmunjom on July 19. Although not completely satisfied
                    with United Nations Command assurances, the Communist side was prepared to
                    proceed with the final arrangements for the armistice. <persName
                        corresp="#p_NILG1">Nam Il</persName> reserved the right to raise the problem
                    of the released prisoners at the political conference, where the Communists <pb
                        facs="0286" n="1404" xml:id="pg_1404"/> wanted the resolution of the
                    problems of handing over the remaining nonrepatriates to the Neutral Nations
                    Repatriation Commission to take place. Finally, the Communist side asked for
                    renegotiation of the line of demarcation. Both sides agreed that it was now time
                    for the plenary sessions to be suspended so that the staff officers could iron
                    out the unresolved details. (Hermes, <hi rend="italic">Truce Tent and Fighting
                        Front</hi>, pages 483–484 and Vatcher, <hi rend="italic">Panmunjom</hi>,
                    pages 199–200)</p>
            </div>
        </body>
